This approach aims to obtain a policy indirectly through the action-value function. Yet, in most cases we don’t actually care about knowing the value of particular states, since all we need is a good policy for our agent.

Here we’ll take a different approach and learn a policy distribution <span class="MathJax_Preview"><span id="MJXp-Span-242" class="MJXp-math"><span id="MJXp-Span-243" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">π</span><span id="MJXp-Span-244" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-245" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">a</span><span id="MJXp-Span-246" class="MJXp-mrow"><span id="MJXp-Span-247" class="MJXp-mo">|</span></span><span id="MJXp-Span-248" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">s</span><span id="MJXp-Span-249" class="MJXp-mo">)</span></span></span> directly – by using <strong>policy gradients</strong>.

<h3 id="Formalism">Formalism</h3>

id="MJXp-Span-814" class="MJXp-mo">.</span></span></span></span></span></span>

This is the “vanilla” version of the policy gradient. We can interpret is as a weighted log-likelihood function. The log-policy is the log-likelihood term we wish to maximize and the total discounted reward acts as a weight: high-return positive trajectories will cause the probability of actions taken during them to increase, and negative-return trajectories will cause the probabilities of actions taken to decrease.

In the following figures we see three trajectories: high-return positive-reward (green), low-return positive-reward (yellow) and negative-return (red) and the action probabilities along the trajectories after the update. Credit: Sergey Levine.

The major drawback of the policy-gradient is it’s high variance, which causes erratic optimization behavior and therefore slow convergence. One reason for this is that the log-policy weight term, <span class="MathJax_Preview"><span id="MJXp-Span-815" class="MJXp-math"><span id="MJXp-Span-816" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">g</span><span id="MJXp-Span-817" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-818" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">τ</span><span id="MJXp-Span-819" class="MJXp-mo">)</span></span></span> can vary wildly between different trajectories, even if they’re similar in actions. Later on we’ll implement the loss and explore some methods of variance reduction.

<h3 id="Landing-on-the-moon-with-policy-gradients">Landing on the moon with policy gradients</h3>

In the spirit of the recent achievements of the Israeli space industry, we’ll apply our reinforcement learning skills to solve a simple game called <strong>LunarLander</strong>.

This game is available as an <code>environment</code> in OpenAI <code>gym</code>.



 <video src="http://gym.openai.com/videos/2019-04-06--My9IiAbqha/LunarLander-v2/original.mp4" autoplay="autoplay" loop="loop" width="300" height="150" data-mce-fragment="1"></video>

In this environment, you need to control the lander and get it to land safely on the moon. To do so, you must apply bottom, right or left thrusters (each are either fully on or fully off) and get it to land within the designated zone as quickly as possible and with minimal wasted fuel.

<h3 id="Training-data">Training data</h3>

The next step is to create data to train on. We need to train on batches of state-action pairs, so that our network can learn to predict the actions.

We’ll split this task into three parts:

<ol>

 <li>Generate a batch of <code>Episode</code>s, by using an <code>Agent</code> that’s playing according to our current policy network. Each <code>Episode</code> object contains the <code>Experience</code> objects created by the agent.</li>

 <li>Calculate the total discounted reward for each state we encountered and action we took. This is our action-value estimate.</li>

 <li>Convert the <code>Episode</code>s into a batch of tensors to train on. Each batch will contain states, action taken per state, reward accrued, and the calculated estimated state-values. These will be stored in a <code>TrainBatch</code> object.</li>

</ol>

<h3 id="Loss-functions">Loss functions</h3>

As usual, we need a loss function to optimize over. We’ll calculate three types of losses:

<ol>

 <li>The causal vanilla policy gradient loss.</li>

 <li>The policy gradient loss, with a baseline to reduce variance.</li>

 <li>An entropy-based loss whos purpose is to diversify the agent’s action selection, and prevent it from being “too sure” about its actions. This loss will be used together with one of the above losses.</li>

</ol>

<h4 id="Entropy-loss">Entropy loss</h4>

The entropy of a probability distribution (in our case the policy), is<span class="MathJax_Preview"><span id="MJXp-Span-1224" class="MJXp-math MJXp-display"><span id="MJXp-Span-1225" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">H</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1226" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1227" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">π</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1228" class="MJXp-mo">)</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1229" class="MJXp-mo">=</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1230" class="MJXp-mo">−</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1231" class="MJXp-munderover"><span class=""><span id="MJXp-Span-1232" class="MJXp-mo"><span class="MJXp-largeop">∑</span></span></span><span class=" MJXp-script"><span id="MJXp-Span-1233" class="MJXp-mrow"><span id="MJXp-Span-1234" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">a</span></span></span></span><span id="MJXp-Span-1235" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">π</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1236" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1237" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">a</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1238" class="MJXp-mrow"><span id="MJXp-Span-1239" class="MJXp-mo">|</span></span><span id="MJXp-Span-1240" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">s</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1241" class="MJXp-mo">)</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1242" class="MJXp-mi">log</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1243" class="MJXp-mo"></span><span id="MJXp-Span-1244" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">π</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1245" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1246" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">a</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1247" class="MJXp-mrow"><span id="MJXp-Span-1248" class="MJXp-mo">|</span></span><span id="MJXp-Span-1249" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">s</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1250" class="MJXp-mo">)</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1251" class="MJXp-mo">.</span></span></span>The entropy is always positive and obtains it’s maximum for a uniform distribution. We’ll use the entropy of the policy as a bonus, i.e. we’ll try to maximize it. The idea is the prevent the policy distribution from becoming too narrow and thus promote the agent’s exploration.

First, we’ll calculate the maximal possible entropy value of the action distribution for a set number of possible actions. This will be used as a normalization term.

This is known as the <strong>REINFORCE</strong> algorithm.

The following block implements a wrapper, <code>train_pg</code> to create all the objects we need in order to train our policy gradient model.

class="o">**</span><span class="n">train_kwargs</span><span class="p">)</span></pre>

The <code>PolicyTrainer</code> class implements the training loop, collects the losses and rewards and provides some useful checkpointing functionality. The training loop will generate batches of episodes and train on them until either:

<ul>

 <li>The average total reward from the last <code>running_mean_len</code> episodes is greater than the <code>target_reward</code>, OR</li>

 <li>The number of generated episodes reached <code>max_episodes</code>.</li>

</ul>

Most of this class is already implemented for you.

You can increase the target reward and use this block to manually tweak your model and hyperparameters a few times.

<h3 id="Experimenting-with-different-losses">Experimenting with different losses</h3>

We’ll now run a few experiments to see the effect of diferent loss functions on the training dynamics. Namely, we’ll try:

<ol>

 <li>Vanilla PG (<code>vpg</code>): No baseline, no entropy</li>

 <li>Baseline PG (<code>bpg</code>): Baseline, no entropy loss</li>

 <li>Entropy PG (<code>epg</code>): No baseline, with entropy loss</li>

 <li>Combined PG (<code>cpg</code>): Baseline, with entropy loss</li>

</ol>

<h2 id="Advantage-Actor-Critic-(AAC)">Advantage Actor-Critic (AAC)</h2>




We have seen that the policy-gradient loss can be interpreted as a log-likelihood of the policy term (selecting a specific action at a specific state), weighted by the future rewards of that choice of action.

However, naïvely weighting by rewards has significant drawbacks in terms of the variance of the resulting gradient. We addressed this by adding a simple baseline term which represented our “expected reward” so that we increase probability of actions leading to trajectories which exceed this expectation and vice-versa.

In this part we’ll explore a more powerful baseline, which is the idea behind the A2C method.

<h3 id="The-advantage-function">The advantage function</h3>

Intuitively, using the advantage function makes sense because it means we’re weighting our policy’s actions according to how advantageous they are compared to other possible actions.

But how will we know <span class="MathJax_Preview"><span id="MJXp-Span-1626" class="MJXp-math"><span id="MJXp-Span-1627" class="MJXp-msubsup"><span id="MJXp-Span-1628" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">v</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1629" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic MJXp-script">π</span></span><span id="MJXp-Span-1630" class="MJXp-mo">(</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1631" class="MJXp-mi MJXp-italic">s</span><span id="MJXp-Span-1632" class="MJXp-mo">)</span></span></span><span id="MathJax-Element-69-Frame" class="MathJax MathJax_Processing" tabindex="0"></span>? <h3 id="Question-1">Question 1</h3>

Explain qualitatively why subtracting a baseline in the policy-gradient helps reduce it’s variance. Specifically, give an example where it helps.

In [35]:

<pre><span class="n">display_answer</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">hw4</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">answers</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">part1_q1</span><span class="p">)</span></pre>

<strong>Your answer:</strong>

The advantage is the amount of how much the current action is better than what we would usually do in that state. In policy gradient methods, we update the policy in the direction of received reward. However, in tcomplicated task, the policy may recive different rewards. Therefor, the policy may need to collect many experiances and average them over the different rewards. With that said, the advantage has lower variance since the baseline compensates for the variance introduced by being in different states.

Imagine that we have two different trajectories in our batch. The first has a positive total reward and the second has a negative one. In this case, it’s easy for the PG to update the policy such that the first trajectory’s actions get higher probability. However, if we add a constant value to our reward function, for example such that the second one receives zero reward, this time the gradient will be completely different since it will not reduce the probabilities for the sends trajectory at all.

Adding a baseline fixes this dependence on absolute values of the rewards, since we’ll compare all rewards to some constant number. In the example above, subtracting a baseline will cause the gradient to be the same in both cases.
